{"id":"2c65a1fad34a","content":"JavaScript\n\nFront End Development\n\nWeb Development\n\nReact\n\nProgramming\n\n4 min read\nJust now\n\n--\n\nHow WildflowerJS brings more ease of use to simple lists\nThe majority of reactive app functionality revolves around the list. Your inbox, your cart, search results, teammates, chats, etc.\nBut in reactive frameworks, rendering and maintaining a list has become an exercise in paper shuffling. Copying an old array into a new array to make a change stick. Registering the change with a reducer, or wrapping it in a setter. Having to learn your framework’s compiler’s opinion about your arrays. The frameworks moved away from the simplicity of JS array functions, and into a meta realm of obscurity and complexity.\nIn WildflowerJS an array is a JavaScript array. You put things in, take things out, move them, shuffle them.\n<div data-component=\"cart\">\n<ul data-list=\"items\" data-key=\"id\">\n<template>\n<li>\n<span data-bind=\"name\"></span>\n<button data-action=\"removeItem\">Remove</button>\n</li>\n</template>\n</ul>\n</div><script src=\"wildflower.min.js\"></script>\n<script>\nwildflower.component('cart', {\nstate: {\nitems: [\n{ id: 1, name: 'Seeds' },\n{ id: 2, name: 'Trowel' },\n{ id: 3, name: 'Watering can' }\n]\n},\nremoveItem(event, element, details) {\nthis.items.splice(details.index, 1);\n}\n});\n</script>\nWildflowerJS has no compilation, no bundler config. The template you see is an HTML <template> element. The list is just a JavaScript array. data-list points at it, data-key keeps rows stable, and data-bind fills in the text. Remove is handled with a data-action calling a function that performs a splice.\nWhat about updates?\nIn WildflowerJS, what is standing between you and an array update? Nothing.\nState in WildflowerJS is plain data that is watched. Everything you already know how to do to an array just works, and the DOM follows.\n// add\nthis.items.push({ id: 4, name: 'Gloves' });// remove\nthis.items.splice(2, 1);\n// change one field on one item\nthis.items[0].name = 'Heirloom seeds';\n// reorder\nthis.items.reverse();\n// replace wholesale\nthis.items = await fetch('/api/items').then(r => r.json());\nWhat is missing? There’s no array copying, no setter functions, no special syntax at all. You mutate the data, the framework works out which text node, which attribute, which row, and touches only that.\nHere’s how to think about it: it’s your array, and the page is looking at it.\nWhat about shared data?\nLists will not always belong to just one component. A cart list shows up in a header badge, in a cart drawer, on a checkout page. At this point, other frameworks might require a state library, with its own vocabulary and its own packages.\nWildflowerJS ships with stores in all distros. A store shares the same state reactivity with components (and plugins, and pools): plain data, watched.\nwildflower.store('cart', {\nstate: {\nitems: [{ id: 1, name: 'Seeds' }]\n},\nadd(item) { this.items.push(item); },\nclear() { this.items = []; }\n});Any component can render that store’s list directly from the template:\n<ul data-list=\"$cart.items\" data-key=\"id\">\n<template>\n<li data-bind=\"name\"></li>\n</template>\n</ul>Again, just one attribute. The header badge, cart drawer, and checkout page all point at $cart.items and a push or splice from anywhere updates all three.\nWhat about mixed rows?\nFeeds may not be uniform. There could be message rows, a photo row, an ad row, a notice row, all in one array, each with different requirements for data and for rendering.\nWildflowerJS adds one more attribute on the list, data-template-key, naming the field that picks each item’s shape, and a data-type tag on each template.\n<div data-list=\"feed\" data-key=\"id\" data-template-key=\"type\">\n<template data-type=\"message\">\n<div class=\"msg\"><b data-bind=\"from\"></b> <span data-bind=\"text\"></span></div>\n</template>\n<template data-type=\"photo\">\n<figure><img data-bind-attr=\"({ src: url })\"><figcaption data-bind=\"caption\"></figcaption></figure>\n</template>\n<template data-type=\"notice\">\n<div class=\"notice\" data-bind=\"text\"></div>\n</template>\n</div>Each item will render through the template matching its type. Change type, it will re-render through the other template. The templates sit next to each other in the markup, as you see above.\nWhat about when the list “grows up”?\nSome lists are more than lists. Dashboard widgets that update four times a second; a visualization with 5000 moving points; a web-based game’s entities. With these, other frameworks may suggest you drop to canvas and manage the DOM yourself to avoid garbage collection and diffing overhead.\nWildflowerJS has a second primitive that can be used for this: data-pool. It is built for per-frame work on thousands of entities. It’s the same mental model you bring to data-list, same attribute style, same declarative markup.\ndata-pool is discussed in detail in this article. Just note that data-list and data-pool, the simple list and the “extreme” list, live in one system, so when your list needs the power of data-pool, it’s a refactor, not a rewrite.\nWhat WildflowerJS doesn’t make you write\nWhat’s missing in our cart example above?\nBuild configuration. Import statements for the list, for the keying, or for the events. There’s no reducer, no action types, no immutable copying. No setter functions. No compiler annotations of your variables. No cleanup code for the event handlers.\nThe list’s an array, the template’s a template. Updating the page is assignment, push, and splice. First-week JavaScript stuff.\nYour list should never have been the hard part. The frameworks just made it feel that way.\nFor more info on WildflowerJS lists, you can see our lists page on our documentation website.\n\nWildflowerJS reaches new developers exactly one way: someone who tried it tells someone else. If you checked out WildflowerJS and find it interesting, please pass on a link to friends. Thanks!"}